{# ══ Review ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call reviewSection() %}
<p>Expand each concept to check your understanding before moving on.</p>

<div class="accordion mt-3" id="u04-review">
  {% call accordion("rev-u04-a", "Inductive reasoning — what makes it distinctive?") %}
  <p>Inductive reasoning moves from specific observations to a general conclusion. It is <em>ampliative</em>: the conclusion goes beyond what the premises strictly establish. Even the strongest inductive argument cannot guarantee its conclusion — new evidence can always overturn it. The goal is to make the conclusion <em>as probable as possible</em>, not certain.</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u04-b", "Strength and cogency — what do they mean?") %}
  <p><strong>Strength</strong> describes how probable the premises make the conclusion. A strong argument offers substantial evidence; a weak one provides little. <strong>Cogency</strong> = strong + true premises. Cogent is to induction what sound is to deduction.</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u04-c", "Three types of inductive argument") %}
  <p><strong>Generalisation</strong>: from a sample to a conclusion about the whole class. <strong>Analogical reasoning</strong>: from the similarity of two cases to a conclusion about the second. <strong>Statistical reasoning</strong>: using quantitative data to support a probabilistic conclusion. Each type has specific criteria for evaluating its strength.</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u04-d", "Fact vs opinion — why does it matter?") %}
  <p>Only factual claims can serve as reliable evidence in an argument. Opinions may be true, but they require support before they can function as premises. Mixing fact and opinion in premises without distinguishing them is a common source of weak arguments.</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u04-e", "Abductive reasoning — a brief note") %}
  <p><strong>Abductive reasoning</strong> (inference to the best explanation) is a third type: given some evidence, what is the most plausible explanation? It is common in medicine, detective work, and science. Unlike induction, it selects from competing hypotheses rather than generalising from a sample. Abductive conclusions are always uncogent in the strict sense — they remain open to revision when a better explanation is found.</p>
  {% endcall %}
</div>

